{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is handler + signature verifier + queue handoff guard. A pure Unit test of HMAC comparison can pass while wiring still forwards invalid bodies. Integration catches the real miss (reject + no enqueue) with in-process module wiring. Rejected higher level: no real OS/network/subprocess behavior is required; in-process HTTP harness is sufficient.","test_description":"Run the webhook route in-process with real signature-validation middleware and a fake/in-memory queue adapter spy. Send a request with mismatched raw body/signature, assert HTTP 401, and assert enqueue was never called.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.23,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"An event is written to the persistent queue before the HTTP 200 acknowledgment is returned to the sender.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is an ordering guarantee across modules (HTTP handler and queue persistence call). Unit tests of one function can miss await/ordering bugs at handoff. Integration with controllable queue write latency catches real failure. Rejected higher level: behavior text does not require real network/OS/subprocess; ordering can be proven in-process.","test_description":"Use in-process server + queue implementation double that exposes write start/finish timestamps and allows delayed resolve. Assert response is not sent before write resolves, then assert 200 after successful write.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.27,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The handler returns the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing of the event to finish.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The bug appears at module boundary between enqueue/dispatch and downstream processor lifecycle. Need wiring-level test to ensure response path is decoupled from processing completion. Rejected higher level: no real OS/network/subprocess is necessary; a slow in-process worker stub reproduces the failure mode.","test_description":"Start route in-process with downstream processor stub that blocks on a promise. Send valid webhook, assert HTTP response returns before unblocking processor, and assert processing eventually completes after release.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even when downstream processing of earlier events is slow and concurrent.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Forcing phrase: \"within 3 seconds wall-clock time\" under \"slow and concurrent\" load. This depends on real runtime scheduling, socket handling, and event-loop contention; mocks can hide timing/concurrency regressions. Adjacent-lower miss-proof: Integration with fake timers/in-process stubs may pass while real server under concurrent requests exceeds SLA. Rejected higher levels: no AI/LLM dependency (not Agentic/Workflow).","test_description":"Run the real Node HTTP server process, issue concurrent webhook traffic while separate downstream workers are intentionally slow, and measure end-to-end response latency with wall-clock timers. Assert p95 (or strict per-request bound) stays under 3 seconds for acknowledgments.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"An event whose ID was already received is not written to the queue a second time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure is idempotency across request handling and persisted queue state; requires module interaction/state handoff, not just local function logic. Rejected higher level: no explicit requirement for real OS/network/subprocess beyond local persistence; deterministic module wiring can expose duplicate-write bug.","test_description":"Use in-process handler wired to real local persistence-backed queue (or realistic in-memory dedupe store used in production path). Submit same event ID twice and assert exactly one persisted queue record/write.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"When the queue reports it is full, the handler returns 503 with a Retry-After header.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior validates mapping of queue backpressure signal to HTTP response contract (status + header), which is a cross-module contract. Unit tests can miss wiring/error-translation faults. Rejected higher level: no need for real OS/network/subprocess if queue-full condition can be produced by an in-process queue module.","test_description":"Run handler in-process with queue adapter configured to return a typed/full-capacity error. Send valid request; assert HTTP 503 and presence/value format of Retry-After header; assert no downstream processing starts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.67,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit and rejects events that would exceed it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This tests queue subsystem behavior against real persistence semantics (local DB/filesystem allowed at Integration). A unit-only test of counters may miss persistence/transaction boundary bugs. Rejected higher level: unless queue is an external service/subprocess, real OS/network is not required; local persistence integration is enough.","test_description":"Instantiate the real persistent queue implementation against a local test DB/filesystem with small configured capacity. Insert up to capacity, then attempt one more event and assert explicit rejection/error and unchanged persisted count.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.07,"Integration":0.61,"System":0.32,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
